Reasoning: 
- cs.RO (Robotics) is the most likely category as the paper deals with inferring geometric constraints in human demonstrations, which is a common problem in robotics. 
- cs.CV (Computer Vision) is also likely as the paper uses kinematic and force/torque information to infer geometric constraints, which can be obtained from visual data. 
- cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another possibility as the paper mentions building constraint models and evaluating them using position, force, and moment criteria, which can be done using machine learning techniques. 
- cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is a possible category as the paper deals with inferring constraints, which is a common problem in AI. 
- cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) is also a possibility as the paper uses instrumented tongs to record human demonstrations, which can be used in human-robot interaction scenarios.
